# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-football-hall-of-fame
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1922-wafl-season] The **1922 WAFL season** was the 38th season of the West Australian Football League.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1922-wafl-season] It saw East Perth equal East Fremantle's feat of winning four consecutive premierships, this time against a rejuvenated West Perth team which had experienced a lean period since 1912.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1922-wafl-season] A consequence of their trip – hastily planned when Subiaco's tour there was cancelled during July – was that their last round match with wooden-spooner Perth was never played – a cancellation to be repeated the following season.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1922-wafl-season] 1922 also saw a dispute with the City of Perth during late June and early July over charges for use of the WACA and Leederville Oval, which led to proposals to play the season's WAFL finals at Claremont Showground, which had not been used for WAFL matches since 1907.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1922-wafl-season] Unlike a similar dispute during 1940 that affected the whole season at Leederville and Perth Oval, however, this dispute only affected a single round of matches, and was resolved before Round 11.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1922-wafl-season] Rules for classification: 1) points; 2) percentage; 3) number of points for.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1923-wafl-season] The **1923 WAFL season** was the 39th season of the West Australian Football League.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1923-wafl-season] It saw East Perth set an unequalled WAFL record of five consecutive premierships, which in major Australian Rules leagues has only been beaten by SANFL club Port Adelaide with six straight from 1954 to 1959 and equalled by Sturt between 1966 and 1970.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1923-wafl-season] The Royals prevailed after two superb games with East Fremantle, who had had its last two home-and-away games cancelled due to undertaking a tour of Victoria and South Australia.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1923-wafl-season] The top four teams was unchanged for the third successive season, and tailender Perth looked likely to suffer a winless season before winning its last match – a fate the Redlegs would suffer again in 2000.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1926-wafl-season] The **1926 WAFL season** was the 42nd season of senior football in Perth, Western Australia.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1926-wafl-season] Claremont, wearing the blue and gold colours of the local swimming club, were admitted at a meeting on 19 August 1925 and made their debut in 1926 but former “B” grade Claremont juniors with established WAFL clubs like Jerry Dolan and Pat Rodriguez were permitted to stay with their current clubs.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1926-wafl-season] Claremont had an exceedingly inexperienced team and were only able to win one game and that by a single point.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1926-wafl-season] Patronisingly called the “babies” in their early years in the WAFL, Claremont were not to finish above second-last in their first ten seasons, and were not helped by being the worst sufferer from the interstate recruiting drives of VFL clubs when the Great Depression began.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1926-wafl-season] With the return of champion coach Phil Matson after he was widely tipped to take over the reins at Richmond, East Perth won their sixth premiership in eight seasons.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1926-wafl-season] West Perth, who had been last in 1924 but had a new grandstand constructed during the season at their eleven-year-old home base of Leederville, rivalled them until September before the Royals showed themselves clearly the best team in the run home.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1926-wafl-season] Subiaco, who had developed what many regard as the best team it ever fielded in the previous season, were disappointing until a stirring run from a mathematical chance for the four drives them to the Grand Final only to be thrashed – a scenario repeated by the Maroons in 1933.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1927-wafl-season] The **1927 WAFL season** was the 43rd season of the West Australian Football League.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1927-wafl-season] It saw the last premiership of the East Perth dynasty dating back to the end of World War I, as mastermind coach Phil Matson was to be killed in a truck crash the following year and the Royals were to fall to a clear last in 1929 as most of their champions retired.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1927-wafl-season] Despite opening their permanent home ground at Claremont Oval, newcomers Claremont-Cottesloe showed little improvement on their debut season and again won only a single game.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1927-wafl-season] The most notable change in fortunes was from South Fremantle, who had their first season with more wins than losses since their last premiership in 1917, and extended Matson's Royals in the grand final.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1932-vfl-grand-final] The **1932 VFL grand final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Richmond Football Club and Carlton Football Club, held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne on 1 October 1932.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1932-vfl-grand-final] It was the 34th annual grand final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1932 VFL season.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1932-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 69,724 spectators, was won by Richmond by a margin of 9 points.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1932-vfl-grand-final] Richmond was competing in its fifth grand final in six years, and, after losing the previous four, finally claimed its third VFL/AFL premiership victory.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1934-wanfl-season] The **1934 WANFL season** was the 50th season of the various incarnations of the Western Australian National Football League.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1934-wanfl-season] Following upon numerous unsuccessful attempts to revive Midland Junction during the 1920s, Bassendean-based Swan Districts were admitted to the competition.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1934-wanfl-season] The 1934 season saw the only finals success during the inter-war period for Perth, who became known as 'Victoria Park' for this season and the following as the Redlegs planned to develop a new oval at Raphael Park.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1934-wanfl-season] Because Parliament failed to pass an Act to allow the club to acquire Raphael Park, however, Perth reverted to their old name two seasons later.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1934-wanfl-season] Old Easts won a seventh successive minor premiership but gave a surprisingly poor display in the Grand Final.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1934-wanfl-season] The 1934 season is most famous, however, for the unprecedented goalkicking success, despite some exceptionally wet Saturdays, of spearheads George Doig and Ted Tyson, both of whom completely smashed previous WANFL goalkicking records.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1934-wanfl-season] In the end, despite neither achieving much on a windy day in the Grand Final, Doig finished with 152 goals and Tyson with 143, tallies not bettered until Bernie Naylor did so in the early 1950s.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1935-wanfl-season] The **1935 WANFL season** was the 51st season of the Western Australian National Football League.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1935-wanfl-season] This season saw Claremont-Cottesloe under new president Pat Rodriguez change its name to "Claremont", and at first gave promise of great improvement before returning to their worst 1934 form.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1935-wanfl-season] 1934 finalists Victoria Park lost defenders Shepherd, A.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1935-wanfl-season] Brown, Hungerford and Patrick Fitzgerald in the off-season to retirement or major injuries and failed to cope with these problems, finishing last for the only time in open-age competition between 1924 and 1980.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1935-wanfl-season] In contrast, Subiaco, who had been disappointing in 1934 with just seven victories, regained Lou Daily from Geelong and Collingwood to signal the end of a major exodus to the VFL.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/1935-wanfl-season] Ultimately the WANFL had no choice but to strike a second medal, which was given to Krepp at the League meeting on 16 October.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] The **Australian Football Hall of Fame** was established in 1996, the centenary year of the Australian Football League, to help recognise the contributions made to the sport of Australian rules football by players, umpires, media personalities, coaches and administrators.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] The inaugural ceremony included 136 inductees, with twelve awarded Legend status.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] As of 2025, this figure has grown to 338, including 33 Legends.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] South Australian goal kicking star Ken Farmer became the most recent inductee to be elevated to Legend status in 2025.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] Since 2015, players, coaches, umpires, administrators and media representatives who have made significant contributions to Australian football – at any level – from the game's inception in 1858 (in the case of players, until at least five years after their retirement) is theoretically eligible.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] A committee considers candidates on the basis of their ability, integrity, sportsmanship and character.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] While the number of games played, coached or umpired, or years of service in the case of administrators and media representatives, is a consideration, it alone does not determine eligibility.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] Players must be retired from the game for at least five years before they become eligible for induction (extended from three years in 2015), while coaches, umpires, administrators and media representatives are eligible immediately upon retirement.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] The committee considers candidates from all states and territories of Australia and from all Australian football competitions within Australia.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] Previous selectors have included Mike Fitzpatrick, Kevin Bartlett, Brendon Gale, historian Col Hutchinson, and broadcasters Harry Gordon, Geoff Christian, Caroline Wilson, Tim Lane, Mike Sheahan, Patrick Smith, Dennis Cometti and Jim Main.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] The *Legends* category is reserved for those who are deemed to have had a significant impact on the game of Australian rules football.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] To date, 30 of the 34 Legends are former players who played the majority of or their entire career in the VFL/AFL, with four players in Barrie Robran, Jack Oatey (SANFL), Merv McIntosh and Bill Walker (WAFL) being selected for careers in other state leagues.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] Being named as a Legend of the Australian Football Hall of Fame is the highest honour which can be bestowed onto an individual Australian footballer.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] As of 2026, there are 34 Legends: this is less than one in 400 (<0.25%) of all VFL/AFL players in history, but the feat is much rarer still when considering the other leagues outside of the VFL/AFL.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] In 2010, several amendments to the Legends category were made to ensure the exclusivity and prestige of the Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p01] In 2023, Barry Cable, an inaugural inductee who had been elevated to Legend status in 2012, had his football honours rescinded after being found guilty of historical child sex abuse.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] Every year there is a special Hall of Fame dinner to announce and welcome the new inductees to the Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] The Hall of Fame inductions started in Melbourne in 1996 to celebrate the VFL-AFL centenary season.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] Ceremonies have only been held outside of Victoria twice, once at Canberra in 2013 and once at Adelaide in 2017.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] In 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the usual annual induction event was not held, and instead the new inductees and legend elevation were announced over four nights in a series of television shows.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] The Hall of Fame has been criticised by football writers and historians for being heavily biased towards figures from Victoria.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] The initial selection committee was made up of 11 Victorians, one South Australian and one Western Australian, with the current selection committee being made up of six Victorians, two Western Australians and one South Australian.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] Of the 136 inaugural inductees into the Hall of Fame, 116 played substantial parts of their careers in Victoria, with eleven of the thirteen "Legends" from Victoria.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] In 2018, the same criticism was levelled by ABC sport reporter James Coventry, who mentioned that over 60% of Legends inducted were either playing or coaching in 1969.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] In 2021, Adam Goodes and Garry McIntosh both declined their nominations to be inducted into the Hall of Fame.
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] Goodes declined his induction due to the lack of support and remedial action taken by the AFL in response to the racial abuse he had endured in his final years playing in the AFL, while McIntosh stated that he "did not play the game for personal honours".
[src:australian-football-hall-of-fame/australian-football-hall-of-fame-p02] Barry Cable was removed from the Hall of Fame in 2023, with his Legend Status being revoked, after he was found civilly liable in a sexual abuse lawsuit.
